oic rape survivor, the burnt-out man-of-feeling, and the hard-hearted Jane Austen herself. These pivotal cases of insensibility illustrate a new theory of mind and of the novel predicated on an essential paradox: the very phenomenon that would appear to halt feeling and plot actually compels them. Contrary to the assumption that fictional investment relies on a richness of interior life, Lee shows instead that nothing incites the passions like dispassion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aFictionxPsychological aspects. 4aEnlightenment philosophy. 4aaffects. 4acharacter. 4acontempt. 4aeighteenth-century literature. 4aemotions. 4ainsensibility. 4anovel. 4apassions. 4asympathy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503607477zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607477.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles